The WebSocket bridge acts as a pass-through to the daemon. You send the same JSON commands you'd use with cavctl, and receive responses.

  Connect:
  const ws = new WebSocket('ws://localhost:8765');

  Send commands (same as daemon protocol):
  // List panes
  ws.send(JSON.stringify({ action: "panes" }));

  // Get pane status
  ws.send(JSON.stringify({ action: "status" }));

  // Add pane
  ws.send(JSON.stringify({ action: "add", name: "worker1" }));

  // Send message to pane
  ws.send(JSON.stringify({
    action: "send",
    name: "worker1",
    message: "Hello",
    cwd: "/path/to/project"
  }));

  // Get pane output
  ws.send(JSON.stringify({ action: "get", name: "worker1" }));

  // Remove pane
  ws.send(JSON.stringify({ action: "rm", name: "worker1" }));

  Receive:
  ws.onmessage = (event) => {
    const msg = JSON.parse(event.data);

    if (msg.type === "response") {
      // Response to your command
      console.log(msg.data);
    } else {
      // Streaming event from daemon (pane output, status changes)
      console.log(msg);
    }
  };

  The bridge broadcasts all daemon events to connected clients, so you'll receive real-time pane output without polling.

